One can use `ord` (to convert character to ascii number) and `chr` (to convert ascii number to character) functions: 

    line = &quot;Ml rfc rp_gj rm Mpceml&quot;
    newline =&quot;&quot;
    for i in range(len(line)):
    	newline += chr(ord(line[i])+2)
    print(newline)

Output: 

    On&quot;the&quot;trail&quot;to&quot;Oregon

The space character is also being converted.

Apparently space is not encoded in original file. So one can exclude it from decoding: 

    line = &quot;Ml rfc rp_gj rm Mpceml&quot;
    newline =&quot;&quot;
    for i in range(len(line)):
    	if line[i] == &#39; &#39;:
    		newline += &#39; &#39;
    	else: 
    		newline += chr(ord(line[i])+2)
    print(newline)

Output: 

    On the trail to Oregon

The if condition can be put in one single line: 

    for i in range(len(line)):
    	newline += &#39; &#39; if line[i] == &#39; &#39; else chr(ord(line[i])+2)

This works for me:

    &gt;&gt;&gt; text = &#39;Ml rfc rp_gj rm Mpceml&#39;
    &gt;&gt;&gt; &#39;&#39;.join(chr(ord(t)+2) if t != &#39; &#39; else t for t in text)
    &#39;On the trail to Oregon&#39;
    &gt;&gt;&gt;

